Conceptual

Question 7

Creating a function to calculate the “Euclidean distance” between two points.

distance_euclidean <- function(x1, x2) {
  # assume that both x1 and x2 are vectors of the same length
  square_diff <- (x1 - x2) ^ 2
  sqrt(sum(square_diff))
}

Storing the data provided in the question as a data.frame

data <- data.frame(x1 = c(0, 2, 0, 0, -1, 1),
                   x2 = c(3, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1),
                   x3 = c(0, 0, 3, 2, 1, 1),
                   y = c("Red", "Red", "Red", "Green", "Green", "Red"))
data

  x1 x2 x3     y
1  0  3  0   Red
2  2  0  0   Red
3  0  1  3   Red
4  0  1  2 Green
5 -1  0  1 Green
6  1  1  1   Red
  1. Computing the Euclidean distance from the test point
test_point <- c(0, 0, 0)
distances <- apply(data[, -4], 1, function(x) distance_euclidean(test_point, x))

distances

[1] 3.000000 2.000000 3.162278 2.236068 1.414214 1.732051

  1. When K=1 the closest observation is observation 5. Thus, the prediction will be Green.

  2. When K=3 the three closest observations will be 2, 5 and 6. Since, 2 and 6 are “Red”, the prediction will be Red.

  3. If the Bayes decision boundary is highly non-linear, then we will expect the best value of K to be large. This is because we will need the model to be more flexible in order to capture the non-linear trend. This is only possible when K is high.

  1. Exploring predictors using scatter-plots
library(ggplot2)

plot_scatter_mpg <- function(var) {
 ggplot(Auto) +
  geom_point(aes({{ var }}, mpg, color = as.factor(cylinders)), 
             size = 2, alpha = 0.7) +
  guides(color = guide_legend("Number of cylinders", "top", title.hjust = 0.5)) +
  theme_custom(base_family = "Inter") 
}

library(patchwork)

plot_scatter_mpg(displacement) + 
  plot_scatter_mpg(horsepower) + 
  plot_scatter_mpg(weight) +
  plot_scatter_mpg(acceleration) +
  plot_layout(ncol = 2, guides = "collect") &
  theme(legend.position = "top")

  1. There seems to be a negative correlation between mpg and the following variables:
  • displacment
  • horsepower and
  • weight

Plus, the number of cylinders also affects mpg. Further, there exists a slight positive correlation between mpg and acceleration. So, these variables can be used as a starting point for the modeling process.
